{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>The Trk system is a low to medium affinity potassium uptake system, widely found in both in bacteria and archaea, where the uptake of K(+) is believed to be linked to H(+) symport [[cite:PUB00042655]]. The core Trk system consists of two proteins, the integral membrane K(+)-translocating protein TrkH (or TrkG), and the regulatory NAD-binding peripheral membrane protein TrkA [[cite:PUB00042656], [cite:PUB00061657], [cite:PUB00099198]]. In Escherichia coli the activity of TrkH is dependent on the ATP-binding protein SapD (also known as TrkE) which is part of the SapABCDF ABC transporter, involved in putrescine export [[cite:PUB00099201]]. Not all Trk systems are dependent on SapD however -it is thought that these may utilise ATP-binding proteins from other ABC transporters [[cite:PUB00042657]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false} {"text" "<p>Sequence analysis of TrkA reveals that the protein consists of 2 tandemly arrayed halves that are 22% identical, a situation that might have arisen through gene duplication. TrkA also exhibits similarity to other Escherichia coli proteins [[cite:PUB00001263]], in particular KefC, a glutathione- regulated efflux protein [[cite:PUB00003817]], and to various dehydrogenase proteins that possess NAD<sup>+</sup>binding sites. TrkA plays a regulatory role on TrkH gating. TrkA, binds ADP in its N2 domain to form a tetrameric ring which closes the channel. When ATP is bound to N1 and N2 domains of TrkA, it induces a tetramer-to-dimer conversion which opens TrkH [[cite:PUB00099198]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR036291", "name" "NAD(P)-binding domain superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"prints" {"PR00335" "KUPTAKETRKA"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Potassium uptake protein TrkA", "short" "K_uptake_TrkA"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-dat